# Node-RED

In this documentation, you will find descriptions and examples of all currently available custom Shelly nodes, as well as instructions on how to enable Node-RED within your Fleet Management instance.

## Enable Node-RED

You need to connect to the database of your Fleet Management instance. Then you should navigate to Schemas -> ui -> Tables -> config. In the config table you should change the json entry in the row with name "node_red_enable" to true.

## The Device node

**![image-20251002-133610.png](data:image/png;base64,)![image-20251002-134006.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

You will see this menu after dragging the device node to the canvas and double clicking it.

![image-20251002-134141.png](data:image/png;base64,)

If you extend the dropdown, you will find a list of all devices that are on your Fleet Manager instance (except for bthome devices; more about them later)

The device node is the start of each of your node red flows. Though the device node you receive all messages that the chosen by you via the dropdown device reports to the Fleet Manager.

## The DeviceFunel node

**![image-20251002-134834.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

When dragged to the flow canvas and double clicked it looks exactly like the device node. It is a filter/funnel that is used in the center of your flows. you connect it on the left to event listeners and on the right to actions. On the device you select the action to which you have connected it will be executed.

Example flow:

![image-20251002-135455.png](data:image/png;base64,)

In this mock flow on turn off of device with Shelly id shellyplugsg3-54320465e1e4 the device named staircase light will be turned on.

If you want to listen for events on one device and execute to the same device - just select that device from the DeviceFunel Dropdown.

## The GroupFunel node

**![image-20251002-140034.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

It works the same way as the DeviceFunel node but instead in the dropdown you choose one of the groups that you have defined in your Fleet Manager instance. Then on certain event an action is executed on a channel of all devices that are members of the chosen group.

## The BluetoothButtonEvent

**![image-20251002-140323.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

![image-20251002-140435.png](data:image/png;base64,)

This node has 3 fields: component name, event and idx (optional, by default 0). You can find the component name of the device in the Fleet Manager:

1\. Open the devices tab

2\. Select the gateway

3\. In the Device Board select the 3 icon

4\. Expand Settings

5\. Scroll until you find it

![image-20251002-142252.png](data:image/png;base64,)

You can choose from 1 out of 3 events - single push, double push, long push.

If you are using a simple button with 1 input - leave the idx blank or type in 0. If you are using the rc 4 button or another button with multiple inputs put in the idx that you need. Beware that they start from 0.

Example flow:

![image-20251002-142600.png](data:image/png;base64,)

In this flow we have connected one rc 4 button to the rooftop light. We are listening to its idx 0 and idx 1.

![image-20251002-142719.png](data:image/png;base64,)

![image-20251002-142750.png](data:image/png;base64,)

If the button with idx 0 is clicked the rooftop light is toggled. If the button with idx 1 is clicked the staircase light is toggled.

## Events

**The OnToggle event**

**![image-20251002-143532.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

When dragged on the flow canvas it appears as:

![image-20251002-143833.png](data:image/png;base64,)

Nodes connected to the upper exit of this node will get triggered on turn on of a particular channel.

Nodes connected to the lower exit of this node will get triggered on turn off of a particular channel.

![image-20251002-144309.png](data:image/png;base64,)

Lets go back to the example from earlier:

![image-20251002-135455.png](data:image/png;base64,)

Plugs only have one channel - 0. That is why here we chose 0 as a channel. If you need to listen for events on multiple channels of the same device - add as many OnToggle nodes in paralel as needed:

Like that:

![image-20251002-144553.png](data:image/png;base64,)

## The OnPower event

**![image-20251002-143602.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

When dragged to the flow canvas, it looks like:

![image-20251002-144657.png](data:image/png;base64,)![image-20251002-144723.png](data:image/png;base64,)

The upper exit is for values that are above what you have put in the "More than" field. The lower exit is for values that are under what you have put in the "Less than" field.

Dont forget to put in the channel that you are interested in. Like OnToggle, you can stack as many parallel OnPower nodes as you need. The same is valid for all nodes.

**![image-20251002-143623.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

## Actions

**![image-20251002-143218.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

Actions are put at the end of the flow.

**The Toggle action**

![image-20251002-143159.png](data:image/png;base64,)

Select a channel on which the action will be executed. Connect the node to the funnels of all devices you want this toggle to be executed on. (See the examples from earlier)

**The TurnOn action**

**![image-20251002-143325.png](data:image/png;base64,)**

\*\*![image-20251002-143352.png](data:image/png;base64,)

Same structure as toggle but here the action is turn on.

**The TurnOff action**

Same structure as toggle but here the action is turn off.

**The Reboot action**

![image-20251002-143407.png](data:image/png;base64,)

The reboot action doesnt have any properties - you dont need to put in anything. Just drag and drop it onto the flow canvas and connect all device funnels of the devices you want to reboot to it.

Reminder:

Dont forget to deploy your flows after making changes.
